      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''Via South America, a Beachfront Boom for South Florida'' (front page, March 12) mentioned several hazards that investors from South America or elsewhere might encounter in their purchase of beachfront properties.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''Via South America, a Beachfront Boom for South Florida'' (front page, March 12) mentioned several hazards that investors from South America or elsewhere might encounter in their purchase of beachfront properties.</p>
        <p>It did not, however, mention the dangers posed by rising ocean levels. Recent studies have indicated that ice melting from glaciers around the world will require the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change to greatly increase its 2001 estimates of the rise in ocean levels in this century. Rising ocean levels make beachfront investment rather hazardous.</p>
        <p>Of course, the greatest risk is to those who actually live on the shores of oceans.</p>
        <p>ANDREW MCLAUGHLIN  Warwick, N.Y., March 12, 2002</p>
      </block>
